  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Leaderboard with Mixed Names</h2>
    <p>When displaying a list of usernames that may include different scripts:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <ul>
        <li><bdi>Alice</bdi>: 15 points</li>
        <li><bdi>محمد</bdi>: 12 points</li>
        <li><bdi>Bob</bdi>: 10 points</li>
        <li><bdi>יעקב</bdi>: 8 points</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Leaderboard example">{{ leaderboardCode | safe }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why Use bdi?</h2>
    <p>The difference becomes clear when RTL text is embedded without isolation:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="With vs without bdi">{{ withoutBdiCode | safe }}</code-block>
    <p>Without <code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code>, the colon and number "3" might appear in unexpected positions when RTL text is present.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Dynamic Content</h2>
    <p>Always wrap user-generated content in <code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code> when you don't know the text direction:</p>
    <div class="example">
      <p>
        Latest comment by <bdi class="username">DemoUser</bdi>:
        <bdi class="comment">This is a sample comment</bdi>
      </p>
    </div>
    <code-block language="html" label="Dynamic content">{{ dynamicContentCode | safe }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Attributes</h2>
    <p>This element supports <a href="/docs/elements/native/states/">global attributes</a>.</p>
    <p>Note: The <code>dir</code> attribute defaults to <code>auto</code> on <code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code> elements, meaning the direction is determined by the element's content.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;bdi&gt;</code> element has no special accessibility role. It purely affects visual rendering of bidirectional text. Screen readers will read the content in its logical order regardless of visual direction.</p>
  </section>

